    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-24T03:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-24T03:10:00-05:00" n="585"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d585">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94112/88: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief of the United States Asiatic Fleet</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Yarnell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief of Naval Operations</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="19" xml:id="d585fn19">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Navy Department.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-24T16:10:00+08:00"
                            >September 24, 1937—4:10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 24—10:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>0024. There is evidence that Japanese are destroying or capturing Chinese fishing
                    vessels and junks. Instances have been reported from Chefoo and Hong Kong and
                    derelict junks have been sighted along the coast. This is of course in violation
                    recognized international law and of Hague Conventions<note n="20"
                        xml:id="d585fn20">See article <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, Convention on
                        Bight of Capture in Naval War, signed at The Hague October 18, 1907, <ref
                            target="frus1907p2#pg_1236">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1907, pt. 2, p.
                        1236</ref>.</note> to which Japan is a signatory.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
